1898_ My visit to "the fair"_ May 30_ Pleasant but very cool_ Fred, Mary, Mr. Gookin & myself left home at 12:30 PM for the fair. Went on the cable to Monroe St. walked to Van_Buren there by the IC_R.R. reached the grounds_ Passed through two buildings hastily, but concluded to spend the time in the Manufactures & Liberal Arts B'd'g_ Saw an exhibit of Vermont Marble on entering. These a curios display of sesoing silks put up by the Belding Co in the form of a steam engine. Cotton & wool fabrics from different states_&c In the exhibit from France we saw gilded furniture, tapestries
Completed

tapestries, fine laces court dresses artificial flowers &c? In the exhibit from Holland we saw some good unclear ware & other porcelains- and found a seat where we could rest awhile The exhibit from the Island of Jamaica consisted mainly of different kinds of hard woods- many preparations of Cassava Root - and a fine collection of ferns - also some native fruits and nuts many of the latter being of medicinal character. A kind of bark which resembles lace when pounded and of which many lovely articles are made- From India elaborate wood carvings, embroidery [in?]] gold thread &c From Japan- paintings wood carving & the most hideous masks in the world-
Completed

We were very pleasantly entertained for a while by Mr Douet?- Commissioner from the Island of Jamaica- From Vienna Austria we saw very costly and most exquisite glass ware- At 6 P.M- heard the chime of bells but as seats were few and far between- hastened our departure- A break in the Cable delayed us on our return- but we arrived safely at 8. P.M-
Completed

2nd visit June 7th? warm with high wind south & disagreeable- Mary & I left home at 12-15 P.M- by the same route as at first- The long walk between the cars is very tiresome We first went to the Fine Arts B'd'g- where we looked for a while at the exhibit of paintings from Holland none of which seemed to me of especial merit- Thence to the Japanese Department where we found Mr Choyo? who showed us much kindness and attentiveness- A long tailed rooster in bronze is very fine also an Ourang Outang carved in wood- We saw some beautiful articles in lacquer work, some carved ivories, and two views of Fuji- one in a round frame- also a
Completed

painting of a Peacock- In the gallery above we saw some very elaborate and beautifully embroidered screens- also paintings an lovely vases- We then went with Mr Choyo to a Tea House built in their peculiar manner, and where we were served with a kind of tea- very green in color, but mild & pleasant to the taste- Some pink & white confections- were also brought us- which were laid on little bits of bark- Each one was presented with a small fern? as a souvenir- We visited the Ohio State B'd'g which has several large pleasant rooms well fitted up- from thence to the Mocousin? Building- a comfortable place where we rested for a time. The next point of interest
Completed

was the Woman's Building in the gallery of which we saw some fine thread laces some valuable old fans &c all in cases- We then went to the Library where we had an appointment to meet Dr. Gale? Rutland why dissapointed us- In this room is a bust of Mrs Harriet Beecher Stowe- After waiting an hour we left for home and on reaching Monroe St found the cable broken again and we waited a half hour in the street- Reached home at 8. P.M much fatigued-
Completed

3rd visit- Weather fine in every way. Mary & I left home at 12/15 P.M Visited the California B'd'g first, which resembles in form one of the old mission houses. It contains a wonderful display of native fruits- and the various products made therefrom- Tall glass jars containing preserved fruits most tempting to the eye- There were also olives and many kinds of nuts- A large dome made of oranges and a tower composed of bottles of olive oil- All the fruit is remarkable for its large size and fine color- We saw a large and highly polished slab in the shape of a half circle, made from one of the large redwood trees- We went next to the Fine
Completed

Arts b'd'g where we first visited the Austrian exhibit. One large picture is striking though disagreeable, representing a fierce fight among one of the leading men of the nation which afterwards led to The thirty years war- One picture of children is very pleasing- A boy is peeling an orange while his sister who stands waiting before him has but little clothing- one stocking- and an apron- In the Italian Section we saw some fine Statuary- two figures of children are very good- One of a young boy with a pleasant face who is holding up a mouse and tantalizing a dog beside him. The other of a girl- holding two puppies in her arms, while the mother is barking
Completed

very good and some of the subjects are interesting.  In the Main Hall of the building  unclear saw a statue of Lincoln in a reclining position and dejected attitude holding the emancipation proclamation in his hand - 
We went next to the Woman's B'd'g on the first floor of which we saw most exquisite embroideries - fine linen doilies, h'dk's, table cloths etc - There is some good china painting.  We saw an interesting collection of large dolls dressed to show the costumes of dif -
Completed

We made a short visit to the Children's b'd'g where we saw the model nursery the play room - the little which cribs etc -
We left at 5 P.M. Mr Choyo accompanying us - 
The cable cars were so crowded that we were compelled to stand all the way which added much to our fatigue - We reached home at 7-30 -
